Here's the route:  enter the Park at 86th Street, go around the east side of the Reservoir (hence I missed seeing the Red-Breasted Mergansers, which were reported from the west side..), over to the Pool, along the Ravine, over to the Meer and the Conservatory Garden, back across the park, exiting around 97th Street.

RANDALL’S ISLAND STATE FIRST RECORD, DAY THREE! Finally got RZ out here for some Rand Redemption, with our ongoing celebrity hummingbird showing beautifully throughout the morning. An overnight cold front ushered in some light late season arrival, which resulted in a quality November birding experience even beyond the immediate vicinity of the Cottage Garden stakeout. Large crowds of observers continued all day in the area around the Urban Farm, with limited sporting activity on the fields elsewhere. Once again, the continuing community enjoyment of our delightful guest would not have been possible without Barbara Davaros and the rest of the Randall’s Island Park Alliance, who created such an inviting stopover site with plenty of floral fuel. Kudos as well to the initial followup team of Adam Cunningham, Efua Peterson, and Brendan Fogarty, who clinched the suspected ID and kicked this whole weekend into overdrive. Clear skies from the start of the day, with TH unexpectedly noting light action from the Leonid meteor shower on the predawn walk across the RFK Bridge. Chillier than the past few days, but still fairly mild and warming up nicely as the sun got higher
Overcast giving way to sunshine in the PM. 79th to 103rd Sts.

Low 50s F, overcast. 110th and Malcom X, around the east side and up the Mount.----===blog post===--I took the day off from work and spent most of it in the north end of Central Park.----At Harlem Meer I saw my first Tree Swallows and Northern Rough-winged Swallows of the year. Red-winged Blackbirds were singing, and I saw a couple of males fighting. I don't know where they're intending to nest, there really isn't suitable habitat now.----At the compost area up on the Mount, I spotted my first Louisiana Waterthrush of the year. ----Nearby, outside the Conservancy Garden and the plant nursery, huge bowers of Red Deadnettle are growing. It's quite pretty, but I can't think it's a deliberate landscaping choice. The Juncos and Chipping Sparrows liked it.----In the Loch, I saw a lot of Swamp Sparrows, which is unusual. There were a couple of more Louisiana Waterthrushes, a couple of Brown Creepers (always delightful), and "Flaco" the escaped/released Eurasian Eagle-Owl was in good view in a habitual roost tree. ----(I saw a report, by the way, that the resident Great Horned Owl was back on Cedar Hill. Yay!)----At the Pool, a couple of Myrtle (Yellow-rumped) Warblers were the first of the season for me.----As I was getting ready to leave, a Blue-gray Gnatcatcher popped up in a bush at the water's edge. Breathtaking! I did gasp at the sight. An extravagantly beautiful male, glowing deep blue.

trip_comments: High 60s F, fair. Went straight up to Summit in the hopes that the large flight last night would mean that it would be very birdy. It was only OK.----===blog post===--I started the morning at Summit Rock, which is often good after a big migratory flight like we had last night. It was... OK. Got my first Least Flycatcher and Pewee of the year, and a lot of of Redstarts and Black-and-white Warblers and singing Magnolia Warblers. ----At Tanners Spring I saw  my first Canada Warbler of the year. Two Scarlet Tanagers came down to just over the Spring. They seemed to be intimidated by a bathing Blue Jay, and didn't come down for a drink. ----I went up to the Loch chasing a reported Golden-winged Warbler. Dipped on it, but my FOY Olive-sided Flycatcher hunted from the high bare branches of a tree over the stream. A couple of hatchouts kept things lively on the ground. My first Blackpolls of the year--their arrival is the traditional marker of the end of migration season, but that isn't so true anymore. Tons of Redstarts,  Black-and-whites, many male Common Yellowthroats, and at least four Northern Waterthrushes. ----More warblers were at the Pool on my way out, including a somewhat late Louisiana Waterthrush. A pair of Gadwall ducks were doing some kind of courtship--he chased her around, giving his little businesslike quack, and she waddled or swam away, fluffed up, and preened. Like a tango.----I had 50 species for the day, 15 warblers. Not bad for me.----Another big migration tonight. Tomorrow is World Migratory Bird Day, and the the Global Big Day, so  you know what I'm doing.

trip_comments: Overcast, mid 40s F. Excellent scanning conditions, with virtually 0 wind, and minimal heat shimmer. Due to the lack of sunshine it felt much chillier than the mid-40s price tag. Was specifically trying to see what was on the bay given the calm conditions, with a particular interest in any Bonaparte’s Gull flocks that were around, but also with alcids in the back of my mind. Plenty of BOGUs, but no other small gulls amongst them, and no alcids, but the duck viewing was relatively good, and a nice surprise. Passerine activity mostly suppressed due to the overcast, and the fact there are not many passerines here in the winter, though Song Sparrows there were seemed plenty responsive to pishing. Governors trust ferry from Battery Maritime Building, since NYC Ferry is not currently visiting the island due to pier repairs.

trip_comments: This fall’s highly anticipated Brant Front Watch on the Dyckman Pier was a roaring success! Perfect conditions for a vismig stakeout on the Hudson, with prolonged, strong northwesterlies throughout the region following Friday and Saturday morning’s rains. Great push of waterfowl, excellent raptor movement, and some nice passerines to round out the list. The Brant flocks showed in abundance, and there were plenty of other seasonal specialties and surprise goodies to be had. The afternoon portion of the vigil was fueled by some delicious pizza. We eventually took a side trip to circle the Dyckman Fields before departing. Joined by a rotating cast of other birders throughout the day, as well as several curious locals
A peaceful and enjoyable morning in the wake of a difficult day. Partly cloudy and warm, with increasing evidence of intensifying migratory activity, including a nice shorebird push in morning flight

trip_comments: first time birding in central park! due to the marathon today it was VERY hard trying to even get into the park, started at central park south & 5th thinking naively that I could enter, the marathon was still going on so had to go along central park south until columbus circle, and then when I thought I could enter park via west 77nd it was also blocked by the marathon had to take a detour to columbus ave and bank due to road blockages, and the only entered the park at around natural history museum front entrance. due to this only had around 30 minutes to spare in the park, so did quick walk around the lake. there was a lot of people, first time in central park so don't know if that's just the normal volume or if its because of maraton and tourists. anyways was hoping to see some ducks in the lake - interesting ducks like diving ducks or mergansers, or shovelors, but didn't see any - there were a lot of people rowing on the lake so that may be part of reason. only saw two mallards with their heads tucked in on the bridge at the north. overall impression is that its really a great place to take photos of birds because they are super used to people and its easy to find them just foraging around, however bad place if you want to record audio since its so noisy. also got to walk around the Ramble a bit and saw a hermit thrush there which is neat, apparently they're very common at this time of migration. ----Few clouds--Temperature: 17°C--Wind: Gentle breeze--Wind Direction: N--Cloud Cover: 20%--Humidity: 40 - 41%--Sunrise: 6:30am--Sunset: 4:48pm

ID confirmed by Mike Shaw of Hawkwatch International's "Ask an Expert." ----Here is Mike Shaw's text:  "This bird is a juvenile (hatched this year) Red-tailed Hawk.  This Eastern subspecies of RTHA is quite a bit paler than the Western subspecies, and this bird certainly is no exception!  Broad-winged Hawks have variable breast streaking (usually localized on the left and right side) unlike this bird's pristine white breast.  BWHA lack the prominent blobby belly band seen here, and their tail bands are much wider (about in the 1/2" range)."

We spent ~35 minutes at the BCHU spot without seeing the bird. The feeder is no longer up, and the only RIPA staff member around didn’t know why it had been taken down. Someone else there had seen the bird around 9:00am so it was at least there (and alive) at some point this morning. The Mexican Sage where the BCHU had been feeding almost exclusively in its first few days is wilting rapidly, but the red salvia where it had also been feeding periodically is still looking pretty good. Apparently that’s where it had been feeding earlier in the morning.

High 60s F, fair. Hunters Gate, Upper Lobe, Ramble Arch, Muggers Woods, south of Tupelo, Gill source, Evodia, around Azalea Pond, Gill, south of Tupelo area, Maintenance. The Red-eyed Vireos have stopped singing, so I assume they've moved on. Our other breeding birds seem too be doing fine.

trip_comments: Exceptional, unforgettable Big Day effort, setting a new record for single day Central Park checklist total. After a week of unfavorable weather conditions, the dam burst overnight and ushered in the hoped for hordes of migrants, as evidenced by impressive radar activity continuing through to just before dawn. We began our quest at the Great Hill ahead of daybreak, where we were inundated with wave after wave of northbound migrants from first light onwards. We spent most of the morning patrolling the North End, making our way to the Reservoir around 11 and reaching 90 species before noon. The Ramble proved to be comparatively quiet, but we still picked up a handful of additional species in the middle section of the Park before returning uptown. After a late lunch skywatch, we revisited some productive sites and secured our 100th species with a Tufted Titmouse at 6:05. We kept on pushing until last light, spotting our final record-breaking bird, Great Blue Heron, at 8:08. All participants agreed that this experience was handily one of the best days of NYC birding in each of our careers to date

The second falcon perched on one of three “ladders” under the northern cable on the east side of the western tower. The first falcon continued north along the New Jersey side. trip_comments: Low 70s F, overcast. String migration last night again, but Summit itself was quite slow. The path down was busier.----===blog post===--Eight and a half hours of birding yielded 53 species for me on this International Migratory Bird Day. A lot of people were out doing big days and birdathons, and many had a lot more, but it's a great total for me. I have to admit that eight hours is a bit much for me these days, even with my current birding style of trying to sit for an hour of so in promising locations. Simply maintaining attention for that long is a challenge.  ----Only one new bird for the year, a Wilson's Warbler at Tanner's Spring. Sixteen total warbler species. ----Biggest miss was Downy Woodpecker. How do I bird for over eight hours and not see a Downy? Most annoying miss was that Gabriel Willow found a singing Alder Flycatcher at Tanner's Spring not to long after I spent an hour there. I saw only one flycatcher, which had no eyering at all and I took to be a Pewee, and I definitely didn't heard any bird calling for "free beer!"----I finally laid eyes on a Yellow Warbler after only hearing them all spring. Still haven't seen or heard a Blue-winged Warbler or Tennessee Warbler (or a bunch or rarer ones), and since I saw my first female Blackpoll today, time is growing short for the spring migration.

Exceptional, unforgettable Big Day effort, setting a new record for single day Central Park checklist total. After a week of unfavorable weather conditions, the dam burst overnight and ushered in the hoped for hordes of migrants, as evidenced by impressive radar activity continuing through to just before dawn. We began our quest at the Great Hill ahead of daybreak, where we were inundated with wave after wave of northbound migrants from first light onwards. We spent most of the morning patrolling the North End, making our way to the Reservoir around 11 and reaching 90 species before noon. The Ramble proved to be comparatively quiet, but we still picked up a handful of additional species in the middle section of the Park before returning uptown. After a late lunch skywatch, we revisited some productive sites and secured our 100th species with a Tufted Titmouse at 6:05. We kept on pushing until last light, spotting our final record-breaking bird, Great Blue Heron, at 8:08. All participants agreed that this experience was handily one of the best days of NYC birding in each of our careers to date

trip_comments: Exceptional, unforgettable Big Day effort, setting a new record for single day Central Park checklist total. After a week of unfavorable weather conditions, the dam burst overnight and ushered in the hoped for hordes of migrants, as evidenced by impressive radar activity continuing through to just before dawn. We began our quest at the Great Hill ahead of daybreak, where we were inundated with wave after wave of northbound migrants from first light onwards. We spent most of the morning patrolling the North End, making our way to the Reservoir around 11 and reaching 90 species before noon. The Ramble proved to be comparatively quiet, but we still picked up a handful of additional species in the middle section of the Park before returning uptown. After a late lunch skywatch, we revisited some productive sites and secured our 100th species with a Tufted Titmouse at 6:05. We kept on pushing until last light, spotting our final record-breaking bird, Great Blue Heron, at 8:08. All participants agreed that this experience was handily one of the best days of NYC birding in each of our careers to date

Simply an incredible day of autumn migration awesomeness, with Randall’s at its best and nearing the seasonal peak of its power. Sustained overnight northerlies after extended rains and unfavorable migration conditions ushered in a solid push of new arrivals. We set a new record for warbler species observed at this site in a single day with an impressive 22 species, backed up by a supporting cast of 10 different species of sparrows. Started off mild with clear skies, becoming sunny and quite warm by midday. Observed several Monarchs and Green Darners migrating, as well as an impressively chunky Groundhog. What a fantastic start to October!

trip_comments: Exceptional, unforgettable Big Day effort, setting a new record for single day Central Park checklist total. After a week of unfavorable weather conditions, the dam burst overnight and ushered in the hoped for hordes of migrants, as evidenced by impressive radar activity continuing through to just before dawn. We began our quest at the Great Hill ahead of daybreak, where we were inundated with wave after wave of northbound migrants from first light onwards. We spent most of the morning patrolling the North End, making our way to the Reservoir around 11 and reaching 90 species before noon. The Ramble proved to be comparatively quiet, but we still picked up a handful of additional species in the middle section of the Park before returning uptown. After a late lunch skywatch, we revisited some productive sites and secured our 100th species with a Tufted Titmouse at 6:05. We kept on pushing until last light, spotting our final record-breaking bird, Great Blue Heron, at 8:08. All participants agreed that this experience was handily one of the best days of NYC birding in each of our careers to date
species_comments: Dramatic influx of birds, with a steady stream of northbound migrants during our dawn skywatch at the Great Hill. Abundant and omnipresent throughout the rest of the Park throughout the day

species_comments: *Rare migrant locally, but regionally expected. I was surprised that this sparrow ended up being a heavily streaked Saltmarsh-type rather than an obvious Nelson’s, since I was particularly on the lookout for the latter. Given that hybrids span the full spectrum in appearance from NESP to SALS, so it can’t be ruled out, but entering it as SALS for now. Vegetation south of the fort. Photos.

Overcast, mid 40s F. Excellent scanning conditions, with virtually 0 wind, and minimal heat shimmer. Due to the lack of sunshine it felt much chillier than the mid-40s price tag. Was specifically trying to see what was on the bay given the calm conditions, with a particular interest in any Bonaparte’s Gull flocks that were around, but also with alcids in the back of my mind. Plenty of BOGUs, but no other small gulls amongst them, and no alcids, but the duck viewing was relatively good, and a nice surprise. Passerine activity mostly suppressed due to the overcast, and the fact there are not many passerines here in the winter, though Song Sparrows there were seemed plenty responsive to pishing. Governors trust ferry from Battery Maritime Building, since NYC Ferry is not currently visiting the island due to pier repairs.
